1. Project Introduction

The Online Voting System (OVS) represents the pinnacle of modern democratic technology. It is designed to replace traditional, error-prone manual voting with a secure, real-time, and tamper-proof digital infrastructure.

1.1 Purpose of the Document

The primary purpose of this SRS is to capture the technical and operational requirements for the OVS. It acts as the definitive source of truth for all project stakeholders, ensuring that the system delivered meets the high standards of accuracy and security required for national-level elections.

2. Overall Project Scope

OVS is a comprehensive ecosystem that includes a public-facing voter portal and a secure administrative dashboard.

2.1 Core Capabilities

  • Biometric-Ready Identification: Using 13-digit unique CNIC validation.
  • Dynamic Election Engine: Create multiple parallel elections with unique rules.
  • Automated Tabulation: High-speed vote counting without human intervention.
  • Audit Trails: cryptographically signing every transaction for future verification.

7. System Constraints & Assumptions

7.1 Implementation Constraints

  • Local Deployment: Currently optimized for enterprise intranet/local server deployment.
  • Database Lite: Implementation uses SQLite3 for maximum portability and zero-configuration setup.

7.2 Critical Assumptions

  • Voters have access to a device with a modern HTML5 compliant web browser.
  • The Administrative network is physically segregated or protected via enterprise-grade firewalls.

8. Cybersecurity & Data Integrity

Security is the foundation of OVS. We implement defense-in-depth strategies.

  • Access Control: Token-based authentication (Bearer JWT) for all privileged API calls.
  • Input Sanitization: Native protection against SQL Injection and Cross-Site Scripting (XSS).
  • Integrity Checks: Database-level unique constraints to prevent "Double Voting" with a 0% error margin.
  • State Immutability: Once a seat (Candidate/Party) receives a vote, its record is locked to prevent administrative tampering.

9. Technical Data Dictionary

Entity Name Attribute Name Data Specification Functional Description
Voters cnic TEXT (Unique) Unique citizen identification string.
Elections status STRING State machine: [CREATED, RUNNING, ENDED].
Parties symbol_path URI / PATH Location of the party's graphical symbol.
Candidates active INT (Binary) Flag for soft-deletion and roster visibility.
Votes voter_cnic TEXT (FK) Reference to the citizen who cast the ballot.

10. Risk Assessment & Mitigation

Identified Risk Probability Impact Mitigation Strategy
Database Corruption Low Critical Implementation of Write-Ahead Logging (WAL).
Unauthorized Access Medium Critical Enforced session tokens and auto-logout.
Power Failure High Medium Transactional commits ensure no data resides in memory.

11. Project Timeline & Lifecycle

The OVS followed the Waterfall SDLC Model for maximum predictability.

  • Phases 1-2: Requirement Gathering (Week 1).
  • Phases 3-4: System Design and Prototyping (Week 2).
  • Phase 5: Backend Core Implementation (Week 3).
  • Phase 6: Frontend Polish and UX Design (Week 4).
  • Phase 7: Documentation, QA, and Delivery (Week 5).

12. Appendices & Glossary

  • CNIC: Computerized National Identity Card.
  • SRS: Software Requirements Specification.
  • ERD: Entity Relationship Diagram.
  • SQL Injection: A vulnerability where malicious code is injected into database queries.
  • Three-Tier Architecture: A client-server architecture in which the user interface, functional process logic, and data storage are developed and maintained as independent modules.
